              <h2>FAQ: Michigan income tax</h2>

              <h3>Is Michigan a flat tax state?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Michigan uses a flat state income tax rate, meaning the
                same percentage applies to all taxable income regardless of how
                much you earn. This is different from progressive systems where
                higher brackets are taxed at higher rates.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Do I pay Michigan tax if I work in Michigan but live in another
                state?
              </h3>
              <p>
                In many cases, non‑residents pay Michigan income tax on income
                earned in Michigan. You may also receive a credit in your home
                state for taxes paid to Michigan. The exact treatment depends on
                your state of residence and any reciprocity agreements, so check
                both states’ rules or consult a tax professional.
              </p>

              <h3>Are retirement benefits taxed in Michigan?</h3>
              <p>
                Social Security retirement benefits are generally exempt from
                Michigan income tax. Other retirement income (pensions, 401(k),
                IRA distributions) may be partially or fully taxable depending
                on your age, year of birth, and the type of plan. The rules are
                detailed and change over time, so always verify with the latest
                Michigan guidance.
              </p>

              <h3>How can I lower my Michigan income tax?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Contribute to pre‑tax retirement accounts (401(k), 403(b),
                  traditional IRA via payroll).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use pre‑tax health benefits such as HSAs and FSAs where
                  available.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Review Michigan‑specific deductions and credits you may
                  qualify for.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Coordinate with a tax professional if you have multiple income
                  sources or live near state borders.
                </li>
              </ul>
